          "body": "At verse 22 the rhetorical mode changes entirely. The casuistic argument of vv. 5-21 — with its cases, conditions, and warnings — yields to doxological declaration. 'Behold, God is exalted in His power; who is a teacher like Him?' (36:22). The rhetorical question is unanswerable and is meant to be. Elihu's cumulative answer to Job's demand to argue his case before God is ultimately not a legal brief but a gesture toward incomprehensibility. God has not appointed anyone His way (36:23); He cannot be corrected. The commanded response is not argument but exaltation: 'Remember that you should exalt His work, of which men have sung' (36:24). The appeal to universal human witness — 'all men have seen it, man beholds from afar' (36:25) — relativizes both Job's specific complaint and Elihu's specific argument. The chapter then closes with the declaration that God is 'great and we do not know Him; the number of His years is unsearchable' (36:26). The irony is complete: Elihu who opened claiming perfect knowledge (36:4) closes confessing that God exceeds human knowledge entirely. Whether Elihu intends this irony or stumbles into it, the text produces it."
