          "body": "The chapter's closing verses describe the water cycle and lightning with a specificity that anticipates God's own questions in chapters 38-39. God draws up drops of water (36:27), distills rain from the mist (36:27), pours it through clouds upon mankind (36:28), and no one can understand the spreading of clouds or the thunder of His pavilion (36:29). His lightning covers the sea's depths (36:30), by these phenomena He judges peoples and gives food (36:31), and He commands the lightning to strike its mark (36:32). The thunder declares His presence (36:33). The pedagogical point is embedded in the causal particle 'for' and 'by these' (vv. 27, 31): the same meteorological phenomena that provide food also execute judgment. Power, provision, and justice are indivisible in God's creation-governance. Jonathan Edwards, in his 'Notes on Natural Philosophy,' observes that nature's patterns are not incidental to theology but revelatory of divine character — every thunderstorm is a sermon. Elihu's meteorological section is not merely poetic filler; it is the theological argument that makes the divine speeches from the whirlwind (38:1) not arbitrary but structurally anticipated. When God asks Job 'Where were you when I laid the foundation of the earth?' (38:4), Elihu has already begun training Job's imagination to receive that question."
